How an LDR (Light Dependent Resistor) Works
What is an LDR (Light Dependent Resistor)?
An LDR is a component that has a (variable) resistance that 
changes with the light intensity that falls upon it. This allows 
them to be used in light sensing circuit. 

The working principle of an LDR is photoconductivity, that is 
nothing but an optical phenomenon. When the light is 
absorbed by the material then the conductivity of the 
material reduces. When the light falls on the LDR, then the 
electrons in the valence band of the material are eager to 
the conduction band.
